[[File:Galician-Celtic princeps - albioni.jpg|thumb|100px|The Nicer Clutosi stele inscription.]]

'''Northwestern Hispano-Celtic''' or '''Gallaecian''' is an extinct language of the [[Celtic languages|Celtic family]], along with [[Celtiberian language|Celtiberian]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Pr<U+00F3>sper|first=Blanca Mar<U+00ED>a|title=Lenguas y religiones prerromanas del occidente de la pen<U+00ED>nsula ib<U+00E9>rica|year=2002|publisher=Ediciones Universidad de Salamanca|isbn=84-7800-818-7|pages=422<U+2013>427}}</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper, B.M. (2005). ''Estudios sobre la fon<U+00E9>tica y la morfolog<U+00ED>a de la lengua celtib<U+00E9>rica'' in ''Vascos, celtas e indoeuropeos. Genes y lenguas'' (coauthored with Villar, Francisco). Ediciones Universidad de Salamanca, pp. 333-350. ISBN 84-7800-530-7.</ref> one of the [[Hispano-Celtic languages|Hispano-Celtic]] group. It was spoken by the [[Gallaeci]] at the beginning of the first millennium CE in the north-western quarter of the [[Iberian Peninsula]], in an area lying between the west and north Atlantic coasts and a line running north-south and linking Oviedo and M<U+00E9>rida.<ref>Jord<U+00E1>n Colera 2007: 750</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Koch|first= John T.|coauthors= |title= Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia| publisher= ABC-CLIO|year= 2006|month=|pages=481|url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=f899xH_quaMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Celtic+Culture:+A+Historical+Encyclopedia&source=bl&ots=p_YAf9xs0E&sig=OAgjXR3_OC9DHv-PJ6g5VweueLw&hl=en&ei=XWMXTJWkHs2GkAWZx-yGCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=hispano-celtic&f=false}}</ref>

== Overview ==
As with the [[Illyrian language|Illyrian]] and [[Ligurian language (ancient)|Ligurian]] languages, the surviving corpus of Gallaecian is composed of isolated words and short sentences contained in local Latin inscriptions or glossed by classical authors, together with a number of names <U+2013> [[anthroponyms]], [[ethnonyms]], [[List of deities|theonyms]], [[toponyms]] <U+2013> contained in inscriptions, or surviving as the names of places, rivers or mountains. In addition, many isolated words of Celtic origin preserved in the present-day Romance languages of north-west Spain are likely to have been inherited from ancient Gallaecian.<ref>Galician words such as ''crica'' ('vulva, ribbon'), from proto-Celtic *k<U+012B>kw<U+0101> ('furrow'), ''laxe'' ('stone slab') from proto-Celtic *<U+03C6>lag<U+0113>n<U+0101> ('broad spearhead'), ''leira'' ('patch, field') from proto-Celtic *<U+03C6>l<U+0101>ryo- ('floor'), and ''alboio'' ('shed, pen') from proto-Celtic *<U+03C6>are-bowyo- ('around-cows').</ref>

The classical authors [[Pomponius Mela]] and [[Pliny the Elder]] wrote about the Celtic and non-Celtic populations of [[Gallaecia]] and [[Lusitania]] but several modern scholars have postulated Lusitanian and Gallaecian as a single archaic Celtic language. Others point to major unresolved problems for this hypothesis, such as the mutually incompatible phonetic features, most notably the proposed preservation of *p and the inconsistent outcome of the vocalic liquid consonants.<ref>Among them the Praestamarci, Supertamarci, Nerii, Artabri, and in general all people living by the seashore except for the Grovi of southern Galicia and northern Portugal: 'Totam Celtici colunt, sed a Durio ad flexum Grovi, fluuntque per eos Avo, Celadus, Nebis, Minius et cui oblivionis cognomen est Limia. Flexus ipse Lambriacam urbem amplexus recipit fluvios Laeron et Ullam. Partem quae prominet Praesamarchi habitant, perque eos Tamaris et Sars flumina non longe orta decurrunt, Tamaris secundum Ebora portum, Sars iuxta turrem Augusti titulo memorabilem. Cetera super Tamarici Nerique incolunt in eo tractu ultimi. Hactenus enim ad occidentem versa litora pertinent. Deinde ad septentriones toto latere terra convertitur a Celtico promunturio ad Pyrenaeum usque. Perpetua eius ora, nisi ubi modici recessus ac parva promunturia sunt, ad Cantabros paene recta est. In ea primum Artabri sunt etiamnum Celticae gentis, deinde Astyres.', Pomponius Mela, Chorographia, III.7-9.</ref><ref>cf. Wodtko 2010: 361-362</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 422 and 430</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 336-338</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2012: 53-55</ref>

Some of the main characteristic of this language, shared with Celtiberian and the other Celtic languages were:
* PIE *-ps-, *-ks- > *-<U+03C7>s- > -s-: place name AVILIOBRIS from *Awilyobri<U+03C7>s 'Windy Hill(fort)',<ref>Curchin 2008: 117</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 357-358</ref> modern place name ''Osmo'' ([[Cenlle]], ''Osamo'' 928 AD) from *U<U+03C7>samo- 'the highest one'.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 282</ref>
* Loss of [[PIE]] *p > *<U+03C6> > 0:<ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 336">Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 336</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 422</ref> place names C(ASTELLO) OLCA from *<U+03C6>olk<U+0101>- 'Overturned', C(ASTELLO) ERITAECO from *<U+03C6>erito- 'surrounded, enclosed', Vagabrobendam from *u<U+03C6>o-gabro-bend<U+0101>;<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2012: 50</ref> personal name ARCELTIUS, from *<U+03C6>ari-kelt-y-os; place name C(ASTELLO) ERCORIOBRI, from *<U+03C6>eri-kor-y-o-brig-s 'Overshooting Hill-Fort'; place name C(ASTELLO) LETIOBRI,<ref>Curchin 2008: 123</ref> from *<U+03C6>le-tyo- 'wide', or *<U+03C6>lei-to- 'grey';<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 269</ref> place name [[Iria Flavia]], from *<U+03C6><U+012B>wery<U+0101>- (nominative *<U+03C6><U+012B>wer<U+012B>) 'fertile' (feminine form);<ref>Delamarre 2012: 165</ref> place name ONTONIA, from *<U+03C6>ont-on- 'path';<ref>Delamarre 2012: 2011</ref> personal name LATRONIUS,<ref>Vallejo 2005: 326</ref> to *<U+03C6>l<U+0101>-tro- 'place; trousers'; personal name ROTAMUS, to *<U+03C6>ro-tamo- 'foremost';<ref>Koch 2011:34</ref> modern place names ''Bama'' ([[Touro, A Coru<U+00F1>a|Touro]], ''Vama'' 912) to *u<U+03C6>am<U+0101>-<ref>Cf. Koch 2011: 76</ref> 'the lowest one, the bottom' (feminine form), ''I<U+00F1>obre'' ([[Rianxo]]) to *<U+03C6>enyo-brig-s<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 377</ref> 'Hill(fort) by the water', ''Bendrade'' ([[Oza dos R<U+00ED>os]]) to *Vindo-<U+03C6>r<U+0101>tem 'White fortress', and ''Baiordo'' ([[Coristanco]]) to *Bagyo-<U+03C6>ritu-, where the second element is proto-Celtic for 'ford'.<ref>Carlos B<U+00FA>a (2007) ''O Thesaurus Paleocallaecus'', p 38-39, in {{cite book|last=Kremer|first=Dieter (ed.)|title=Onom<U+00E1>stica galega : con especial consideraci<U+00F3>n da situaci<U+00F3>n prerromana : actas do primeiro Coloquio de Trier 19 e 20 de maio de 2006|year=2007|publisher=Universidade de Santiago de Compostela|location=Santiago de Compostela|isbn=978-84-9750-794-3}}</ref>
* Vocalization of inter-consonantic sonants: *n<U+0325>, *m<U+0325> > an, am; *r<U+0325>, *l<U+0325> > ri, li:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 342.</ref> place name ''Brigantia'' from *Brg-nt-y-<U+0101> 'The towering one, the high one'; place names NEMETOBRIGA, COELIOBRIGA, TALABRIGA with second element *brig<U+0101> 'high place',<ref>Luj<U+00E1>n 2006: 727-729</ref> and AVILIOBRIS, MIOBRI, AGUBRI with second element *bris < *brixs < *brigs.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 357-382</ref>
* Reduction of diphthong *ei > <U+0113>: theonym DEVORI, from *d<U+0113>wor<U+012B>g<U+0113> < *deiwo-r<U+0113>g-ei 'To the king of the gods'.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 338; Jord<U+00E1>n C<U+00F3>lera 2007: 754.</ref>
* Lenition of *m in the group *-mnV- > -unV-:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 425-426.</ref><ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 336.</ref> ARIOUNIS MINCOSEGAECIS, dative form from *ar-yo-mno- *menekko-seg-<U+0101>k-yo- 'To the (deities of the) fields of the many crops'.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 205-215.</ref>
* Assimilation *p .. k<U+02B7> > *k<U+02B7> .. k<U+02B7>: tribe name ''Querquerni'' from *perk<U+02B7>- 'oak, tree'.<ref>Luj<U+00E1>n 2006: 724</ref> Although this name has also been interpreted as Lusitanian by B. M. Pr<U+00F3>sper,<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 397</ref> she proposed recently for that language a *p .. k<U+02B7> > *k<U+02B7> .. k<U+02B7> > *p .. p assimilation.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pr<U+00F3>sper|first=B. M.|coauthors=Francisco Villar|title=NUEVA INSCRIPCI<U+00D3>N LUSITANA PROCEDENTE DE PORTALEGRE|journal=EMERITA, Revista de Ling<U+00FC><U+00ED>stica y Filolog<U+00ED>a Cl<U+00E1>sica (EM)|year=2009|volume=LXXVII|issue=1|pages=1<U+2013>32|url=http://emerita.revistas.csic.es/index.php/emerita/article/view/304/313|accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>
* Reduction of diphthong *ew > ow, and eventually <U+014D>:<ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 423">Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 423.</ref> personal names TOUTONUS / TOTONUS; personal names CLOUTIUS, but VESUCLOTI 'having good fame' < *Wesu-kleutos or *Wesu-kleut-yos.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 211</ref> In Celtiberian the forms ''toutinikum/totinikum'', from  *teut- > *tout- 'nation, tribe', show the same process.<ref>Jord<U+00E1>n C<U+00F3>lera 2007: 755</ref>
* Superlatives in -is(s)amo:<ref name="Wodtko 2010: 356">Wodtko 2010: 356</ref> place names BERISAMO < *Bergisamo- 'The highest one',<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 266, 278</ref> SESMACA < *Segisam<U+0101>-k<U+0101> 'The strongest one, the most victorious one'.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 423</ref> The same etymology has been proposed for the modern place names ''S<U+00E9>samo'' ([[Culleredo]]) and ''S<U+00ED>samo'' ([[Carballo]]), from *Segisamo-.<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 282.</ref>

Some characteristics of this language not shared by Celtiberian:
* In contact with *e or *i, intervocalic *-g- > 0:<ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 423"/> theonym DEVORI from *d<U+0113>wor<U+012B>g<U+0113> 'To the king of the gods'; adjective derived of a place name SESMACAE < *Segisam<U+0101>-k<U+0101>; personal names MEIDUENUS < *Medu-genos 'Born of mead', CATUENUS < *Katu-genos 'Born of the fight';<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 266</ref> inscription NIMIDI FIDUENEARUM HIC < *widu-gen-y<U+0101>.<ref name="Wodtko 2010: 356"/> But Celtiberian place name SEGISAMA and personal name ''mezukenos'' show preservation of /g/.<ref>Jord<U+00E1>n C<U+00F3>lera 2007: 763-764.</ref>
* *-lw-, *-rw- > -l<U+03B2>-, -r<U+03B2>- (as in Goidelic):<ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 336"/> MARTI TARBUCELI < *tarwo-okel- 'To Mars of the Hill of the Bull', but Celtiberian TARVODURESCA.
* Late preservation of the group *(-)<U+03C6>l- > (-)<U+03B2>l-, only later > (-)l-:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 422, 427</ref><ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 345">Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 345</ref> place names BLETISAM(AM), BLETIS(AMA), modern Ledesma ([[Boqueix<U+00F3>n]]) < *<U+03C6>letisam<U+0101>;  BLANIOBRENSI,<ref>Sometimes it has been read ELANIOBRENSI</ref> medieval Laniobre < *<U+03C6>l<U+0101>n-yo-bri.<ref>Luj<U+00E1>n 2006: 727</ref> But Celtiberian place name ''Letaisama''.<ref>Jord<U+00E1>n C<U+00F3>lera 2007: 757.</ref>
* *wl- is maintained:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 426</ref> VLANA < *wl<U+0325>Hn-eh<U+2082>, while Celtiberian has l-: launi < *wl<U+0325>H-mn-ih<U+2082> (?).
* Sometimes *wo- > wa-:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 346</ref> VACORIA < *(d)wo-koryo- 'who has two armies', VAGABROBENDAM < *u<U+03C6>o-gabro-.
* Dative plural ending -bo < *b<U+02B0>o, while Celtiberian had -bos:<ref name="Pr<U+00F3>sper 2005: 345"/> LUGOUBU/LUCUBO 'To (the three gods) Lug'.

Gallaecian appears to be a [[Q-Celtic]] language, as evidenced by the following occurrences in local inscriptions: ARQVI, ARCVIVS, ARQVIENOBO, ARQVIENI[S], ARQVIVS, all probably from IE Paleo-Hispanic *ark<U+02B7>ios 'archer, bowman', retaining [[proto-Celtic]] *k<U+02B7>.<ref name=koch2011>{{cite book|last=Koch|first=John T|title=Tartessian 2: The Inscription of Mesas do Castelinho ro and the Verbal Complex. Preliminaries to Historical Phonology|year=2011|url=http://www.oxbowbooks.com/bookinfo.cfm/ID/91450//Location/Oxbow|publisher=Oxbow Books, Oxford, UK|isbn=978-1-907029-07-3|pages=53<U+2013>54,144<U+2013>145}}</ref> It is also noteworthy the ethnonyms ''Equaesi'' ( < PIE *ek<U+0302>wos 'horse'), a people from southern Gallaecia,<ref>Cf. Vallejo 2005: 321, who wrongly assign them to the [[Astures]].</ref> and the ''Querquerni'' ( < *perk<U+02B7>- 'oak'). Nevertheless, two modern toponyms have been interpreted as showing kw / k<U+02B7> > p:<ref>Pr<U+00F3>sper 2002: 422, 378-379</ref> ''Panti<U+00F1>obre'' ([[Arz<U+00FA>a]], composite of *k<U+02B7>antin-yo- '(of the) valley' and *brixs 'hill(fort)') and ''Pezobre'' ([[Santiso]], from *kweityo-bris).

